Each of the Co-Tenants and the Manager may also sometimes be referred to in this Agreement as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties". RECITALS A. The Co-Tenants are developing and will construct, own and operate a photovoltaic solar project with a maximum aggregate capacity of approximately 370 MW (collectively, the "Project") located in Maricopa, Arizona. B. Each Co-Tenant will construct, own and operate a separate and discrete number of photovoltaic panels, current inverters and other assets (each, a "Phase") of the Project, all of which collectively will comprise the Project. C. The Phases to be constructed, owned and operated by each of the Co-Tenants are projected to have a net nameplate capacity of 152 MW for Mesquite Solar 3 and a combined net nameplate capacity of 218 MW for SEP II and SGS Development. D. The Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, have entered into that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the Co-Tenants, San Diego Gas & Electric Company ("SDG&E") and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the "CAISO"), dated as of April 19, 2016, together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto (as may be further amended or supplemented, the "LGIA") for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for the Project and each of the Phases. E. The Parties desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the terms and conditions under which the Co-Tenants will be co-tenants under the LGIA and share the obligations thereunder, the Manager shall act as the Co-Tenants' manager to administer and manage the LGIA on behalf of the Co-Tenants in relation to the CAISO and SDG&E, and certain other related matters. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and the agreements and covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereto agree as follows: AGREEMENT ARTICLE I DEFINITIONS 1.1 Certain Definitions. Capitalized words and phrases used herein shall have the following meanings, or the meanings given in the Sections of this Agreement in which they are defined, unless the text expressly or by necessary implication requires otherwise. (a) "Agreement" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement, and includes all exhibits and appendices hereto. (b) "Applicable Laws and Regulations" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (c) "Arbitration Rules" has the meaning given forth in Section 2.14(b). (d) "Bankruptcy" means any case, action or proceeding under any bankruptcy, reorganization, insolvency or receivership law or any dissolution or liquidation proceeding commenced by or against a Person and, if such case, action or proceeding is not commenced by such Person, such case or proceeding shall be consented to or acquiesced in by such Person or shall result in an order for relief, or shall remain undismissed for ninety (90) days. (l) "Effective Date" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. (m) "Emergency Condition" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (n) "Events of Default" has the meaning given in Section 2.10. (o) "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor agency. (p) "Financing Party" means any and all lenders providing senior or subordinated construction, interim or long-term debt financing or refinancing (including hedging counterparties) for the development, construction, purchase or operation of a Phase and any trustee or agent acting on behalf of any such lenders. (q) "Force Majeure" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (r) "FPA" has the meaning given in Section 2.9(a). (s) "General Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 2.10. (t) "Good Utility Practice" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (u) "Indemnified Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2.8(a). (v) "Indemnifying Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2.8(a). (w) "Insolvent Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 4.3(e). (x) "Inter-Phase Shared Facilities Agreement" means that certain Amended and Restated Co-Tenancy and Shared Facilities Agreement, dated as of December 17, 2015, by and among Mesquite Solar 1, LLC, Mesquite Solar 2, LLC, Mesquite Solar 3, LLC, SEP II, LLC and Sempra Global Services, Inc. (y) "Interconnection Customer" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (z) "Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (aa) "Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (bb) "Interest Rate" means the lesser of (a) the prime rate as published in "The Money Rates" Section of The Wall Street Journal (U.S. Edition), plus four percent (4.00%) per annum and (b) the highest rate permitted under Applicable Laws and Regulations. (cc) "Large Generating Facility" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (dd) "LGIA" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. (ee) "LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses" means (i) all amounts due and payable under the LGIA to the CAISO or the Participating TO, and (ii) all costs and expenses necessary or appropriate for the Manager to incur or pay in connection with administering and managing the LGIA, including in connection with affirmative covenants with respect to maintenance of the Project and the Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, communications with CAISO, insurance and reporting, and SDG&E charges related to the operation and maintenance of the Participating TO's Interconnection Facilities. (ff) "Manager" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. (gg) "Mesquite Solar 3" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. (hh) "Manager Representative" has the meaning given in Section 5.13. (ii) "MW" means a megawatt or megawatts AC, as the context may require. (jj) "NERC" means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or its successor organization. (kk) "Network Upgrades" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (ll) "Notice of Dispute" has the meaning given in Section 2.14(a). (mm) "Participating TO" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (nn) "Participating TO's Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (oo) "Party" and "Parties" have the meanings given in the preamble to this Agreement. (pp) "Payment Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 2.10. (qq) "Percentage Interest" means, with respect to each Co-Tenant, as of any date of determination, the ratio (expressed as a percentage) of (X) divided by (Y), where (X) equals the Capacity of the Co-Tenant's Phase, provided that (X) equals zero (0) if such Co-Tenant's Phase has not (in part or in full) initially synchronized with the CAISO grid; and (Y) equals the sum of the Capacities in respect of all Phases which have (in part or in full) initially synchronized with the CAISO grid. (rr) "Person" means any individual or entity, and the heirs, personal representatives, successors and assigns of such individual or entity where the context so permits. (ss) "Phase" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. (tt) "Phase 1" means the solar energy electric generating facility to be developed, owned and operated by Mesquite Solar 3 (or its successor or permitted assign) located in Maricopa, Arizona, with a maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit A. (uu) "Phase 2" means the solar energy electric generating facility to be developed, owned and operated by SEP II (or its successor or permitted assign) located in Maricopa, Arizona, with a maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit A. (vv) "Phase 3" means the solar energy electric generating facility to be developed, owned and operated by SGS Development (or its successor or permitted assign) located in Maricopa, Arizona, with a maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit A. (ww) "Phase Controlled Assets" means, for each Co-Tenant, any of the assets comprising its respective Phase, the corresponding Phase Real Property and related Phase agreements and contractual arrangements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Phase Controlled Assets shall exclude the LGIA. (xx) "Phase Real Property" means, for any Phase, the real property interests utilized by such Phase. (yy) "Point of Interconnection" has the meaning given in the LGIA. (zz) "Project" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. (aaa) "SDG&E" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. (bbb) "SEP II" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. (ccc) "SGS Development" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. (ddd) "Shortfall" has the meaning given in Section 2.3(b)(ii). (eee) "Solvent Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 4.3(e). (fff) "Terminated Party" has the meaning given in Section 4.6. (ggg) "Transfer" means, with respect to any asset, the sale, assignment, transfer, pledge, encumbrance, transfer, or other disposition, either voluntarily, by operation of law or otherwise, of such asset. "Transferee" shall be interpreted accordingly. (hhh) "Undivided Interest" has the meaning given in Section 2.1. ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Phase owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors or permitted assigns) at the Point of Interconnection. Each Co-Tenant shall have an undivided ownership interest (each, an "Undivided Interest") as tenant-in-common in the rights and obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, and possess an undivided right to enjoy all of such Undivided Interest, all in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. 2.2 Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Phase to the Point of Interconnection to the extent the installed capacity of such Phase exceeds its Capacity. Subject to Section 2.7, to the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant delivering energy to the Point of Interconnection from its respective Phase in excess of the Capacity in respect of such Phase, then such Co-Tenant shall at its expense immediately curtail the operation of its Phase so as not to exceed its Capacity. 2.3 Curtailment. (a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.3, direct the Co-Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. (b) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, such curtailment shall be allocated in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved: (i) first, each Co-Tenant (if any) who is delivering energy in excess of such Co-Tenant's Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Co-Tenant's Capacity, and (ii) second, each Co-Tenant shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount equal to (X) minus (Y) (for each Co-Tenant, such amount, in MW, being referred to as the "Curtailed Output Cap"); where (X) equals such Co-Tenant's Capacity, and (Y) equals the product of (A) and (B); and where (A) equals the aggregate number of MW then required for the Project to curtail (after application of preceding clause (i)) and (B) equals such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest; provided that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Co-Tenant is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") because such Co-Tenant's Phase is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or due to any other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, the Manager shall use reasonable efforts to authorize each other Co-Tenant to generate above such Co-Tenant's Curtailed Output Cap by allocating among such other Co-Tenants the Shortfall on a pro-rata basis in accordance with such other Co-Tenants' Percentage Interests. (c) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 2.3: (i) The Manager shall be authorized to curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Co-Tenants to comply with this Section 2.3, curtailment of interconnection services directed by the CAISO or Participating TO is not otherwise achievable, or (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each of the foregoing cases (A) and (B), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA; and (ii) To the extent that the need for any interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant's Phase or portions of its Phase or the failure of such Phase to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Tenant under the LGIA or an applicable power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Tenant's Phase is the cause of an Emergency Condition, then all such curtailment shall be allocated to such Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities, and damages resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Phase or such portions of the Phase, as the case may be. (d) Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.3 upon notice from the Manager. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may effect the same by direct action. 2.4 LGIA Third Party Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the payment of all expenses incurred in connection with the LGIA in accordance with the following provisions: (a) LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, any capital expenditures arising out of any upgrades or facilities required to interconnect any particular Phase shall be for the sole account of such Phase and its Co-Tenant. (b) Collection and Payment of LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses. The Manager shall, as authorized representative for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection, payment and reimbursement of the LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer under or in connection with the LGIA. The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing the Co-Tenants their respective pro rata shares of such LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses and providing backup documentation for such invoices. The Manager shall establish procedures for invoicing and collecting payments from Co-Tenants in order to enable the Manager and Co-Tenants to achieve the payment requirements under and in connection with the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to audit, and receive periodic supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant hereunder. 2.5 Liquidated Damages; Credits; Refunds. To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). 2.6 Joint and Several Liability. Notwithstanding any other provision hereof, each Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that under the LGIA it is jointly and severally liable for (a) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer, including the financing of all Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades that are required to be financed by the Interconnection Customer in order to accommodate the interconnection of the entire Project, and (b) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided that a Co-Tenant's joint and several liability under the LGIA shall not diminish or impair any Co-Tenant's rights to reimbursement or contribution from another Co-Tenant hereunder in respect of obligations of another Co-Tenant. Each Co-Tenant further acknowledges and agrees that, for the purposes of the LGIA, (i) the entire gross generator capacity of 370 MW comprising the Project shall be considered to be a single Large Generating Facility, (ii) no Co-Tenant may have any expectation that the CAISO will treat any portion of the Project as a stand-alone Large Generating Facility or differently from any other portion of the Large Generating Facility, (iii) Co-Tenants shall act as a single entity in undertaking the obligations of Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, (iv) CAISO and Participating TO shall treat all Co-Tenants comprising the Interconnection Customer as a single entity under the LGIA and bear no obligation or responsibility to any individual Co-Tenant and (v) performance of the Interconnection Customer's obligations under the LGIA shall not be excused by reason of any other Co-Tenant's failure to agree with respect to any obligation of the Interconnection Customer thereunder. 2.7 Capacity. (a) The Capacity with respect to any Phase shall be increased only upon receipt by such Phase's Co-Tenant of written consent to such increase provided by all of the other Parties, the CAISO and the Participating TO, such consent to be provided in each such party's sole discretion. (b) The Capacity with respect to any Phase shall be decreased only upon receipt by such Phase's Co-Tenant of written consent to such decrease provided by (i) the CAISO and the Participating TO, such consent to be provided in each such party's sole discretion, and (ii) the other Parties, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld (it being acknowledged and agreed that it would be unreasonable for a Party to withhold such consent solely because such decrease would result in a change in such withholding Party's Percentage Interest). 2.8 Indemnity. (a) Subject to the limitations provided in Section 5.11, each Co-Tenant (an "Indemnifying Co-Tenant") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (each, an "Indemnified Co-Tenant") and the Manager from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees (collectively, "Claims"), which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or the Manager or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant or the Manager as a result of any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant. (b) Subject to the limitations provided in Sections 3.3(c) and 5.11, the Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager. 2.9 Operation and Management; Insurance. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Phase Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (i) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (ii) in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (iii) in compliance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended ("FPA"), and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (iv) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (v) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC and WECC, and (vi) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Costs & Operating Expenses. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to the Manager as a representative for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide the Manager such information required by the Manager to comply with its obligations under the LGIA. (d) Each Co-Tenant shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of the LGIA (including Section 18.3 of the LGIA) and Exhibit B hereto. 2.10 Events of Default; Default. The following shall constitute "Events of Default": a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (a) ten (10) days ("Payment Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (b) twenty (20) days ("General Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of any default (other than a payment default), provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than twenty (20) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Party shall not be in default under this Section 2.10 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed ninety (90) days, including the initial cure period. 2.11 Remedies. Subject to the last sentence of Section 5.8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative): (a) Following an Event of Default by a Co-Tenant, the non-defaulting Co-Tenant or Co-Tenants, or the Manager on behalf of itself or the other Co-Tenant(s), shall have the following remedies, exercisable only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable: (i) In their sole and absolute discretion, to cure the default of the defaulting Co-Tenant by making or tendering the required payment or performance, and permitting the defaulting Co-Tenant's Phase to continue to exercise its rights under the LGIA, provided that any such amounts paid by the non-defaulting Co-Tenant(s) shall be treated as a loan to the defaulting Co-Tenant, which loan shall accrue interest until repaid in full at the Interest Rate; (ii) To demand disconnection of the defaulting Co-Tenant's Phase in accordance with Section 2.12 hereof, provided, that (A) the Manager shall have in good faith determined that bringing an action for money damages and/or for specific performance will not provide an adequate or timely remedy for such default, (B) the defaulting Co-Tenant's Phase shall be permitted to reconnect promptly when and if the default is cured, and (C) in the case of any such reconnection, any and all damage suffered and incurred by the non-defaulting Co-Tenants and the Manager have been compensated; (iii) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; and/or (iv) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which the nondefaulting Co-Tenant or Co-Tenants or the Manager might otherwise have at law or in equity. (b) Following an Event of Default by the Manager, the Co-Tenants shall have the following remedies, exercisable only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable: (i) To remove the Manager for cause, as permitted by Section 3.5; (ii) In their sole discretion, cure the default of the Manager, provided any amounts paid shall be recoverable from the Manager, subject to the limitations of liability set forth in Section 3.3(c); (iii) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; and/or (iv) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which any one or more of the Co-Tenants might otherwise have at law or in equity. (c) In the event a Party in Bankruptcy seeks to assume, or assume and assign, this Agreement pursuant to 11 U.S.C. 365, such Party shall at the time of such assumption cure all defaults, or provide to the non-bankrupt Parties adequate assurance that it or its assignee will promptly cure all defaults under this Agreement. The Parties agree that the following will constitute adequate assurance of a prompt cure under 11 U.S.C. 365: (i) The payment, on the date of entry of an order by the bankruptcy court approving the assumption, or assumption and assignment, by the Party in Bankruptcy or its assignee of, sufficient funds to the non-bankrupt Parties to fully cure all financial defaults under this Agreement; and (ii) The provision by the Party in Bankruptcy or its assignee of such insurance, bonding, or other financial commitments which will enable the interconnection of the Project pursuant to the LGIA (including, without limitation, such Party's Phase) to remain undisrupted, and which in the sole reasonable opinion of the non-bankrupt Parties will adequately assure the future operations of the non-bankrupt Parties under this Agreement. Availability of Insurance on Commercially Reasonable Terms. In the event any insurance (including the limits or deductibles thereof) required hereunder to be maintained, other than insurance required by law to be maintained, shall not be available and commercially reasonable terms in the commercial insurance market, Manager shall not unreasonably withhold its agreement to waive such requirement to the extent the maintenance thereof is not so available; provided, however, that (i) the applicable Co-Tenant shall first request any such waiver in writing, which request shall be accompanied by written reports prepared by such Co-Tenant certifying that such insurance is not available on commercially reasonable terms in the commercial insurance market for electric generating plants of similar type and capacity (and, in any case where the required amount is not so available, certifying as to the maximum amount which is so available) and explaining in detail the basis for such conclusions and the form and substance of such reports to be reasonably acceptable to the Manager; (ii) at any time after the granting of any such waiver, the Manager may request, and the applicable Co-Tenant shall furnish to the Manager within fifteen (15) days after such request, supplemental reports reasonably acceptable to the Manager updating the prior reports and reaffirming such conclusion; (iii) any such waiver shall be effective only so long as such insurance shall not be available on commercially reasonable terms in the commercial insurance market, it being understood that the failure of a Co-Tenant to timely furnish any such supplemental report shall be conclusive evidence that such waiver is no longer effective because such condition no longer exists; and (iv) such Co-Tenant shall indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and the other Co-Tenants for any losses sustained by them as a result of coverages required under this Agreement that have not been obtained by such Co-Tenant as a result of this section. For purposes of this Agreement, if the aggregate premiums to be paid for the renewal of all of the insurance required to be provided hereunder, when taken as a whole, are no more than the greater of (i) 110% of the amount of the premiums paid for the prior renewal or (ii) the amount budgeted for such renewal at any time in the immediately preceding five (5) years, such insurance shall be deemed to be commercially reasonable. 15. Conflict with a Co-Tenant's Financing Arrangements. In the event that compliance with any insurance (including the limits or deductibles thereof) required hereunder is in conflict with a Co-Tenant's obligations under any financing documents between the such Co-Tenant and any applicable Financing Parties, the provisions of such financing documents shall prevail so as to ensure that the such Co-Tenant is not in default of such requirements, as determined by the Co-Tenants in consultation with Financing Parties; provided that, in any event, such Co-Tenant shall indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and the other Co-Tenants for any losses sustained by them as a result of coverages required under this Agreement that have not been obtained by such Co-Tenant as a result of this section. 16. Indemnity. In the event that any Co-Tenant fails to comply with any insurance (including the limits or deductibles thereof) required hereunder, such Co-Tenant shall indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and the other Co-Tenants for any losses sustained by them as a result of such failure.
